Our analyses mainly leverage on a set packages that are currently maintained at the Cancer Data Science Laboratory, University of Trieste. Packages websites provide detailed function manuals and reference vignettes, upon which these analyses are largely based on.




Requirements

We assume that you have installed the following packages and their dependencies

# Our packages
library(mobster)
library(CNAqc)
library(ctree)

# Other packages
library(dplyr)
library(readr)
library(ggplot2)

Input data

We use some data that we have recently analysed; there are more data release with our paper, you could play around with those once you have understood this analysis.

Subclonal reconstruction of tumors by using machine learning and population genetics Caravagna et al.Nature Genetics volume 52, pages 898907 (2020).

For these data we have selected the following:

  • single-nucleotide somatic mutations;
  • absolute clonal CNA segments;
  • tumour purity.

The data have been cleaned by me for this presentation (similarly to how I did that for the actual paper). Originally, this sample and its associated relapse have been released with a Cancer Cell paper

Evolutionary Trajectories of IDH WT Glioblastomas Reveal a Common Path of Early Tumorigenesis Instigated Years ahead of Initial Diagnosis. Koerber et al.Cancer Cell. 2019 Apr 15;35(4):692-704.e12.

Inputs are provided in CSV format, we load them using the readr package.

# -> somatic mutations
snvs = readr::read_csv('data/mutations.csv', col_types = readr::cols())

# -> copy number segment (CNA), precisely absolute calls for clonal segments
cna = readr::read_csv('data/cna.csv', col_types = readr::cols())

# Sample information
sample_info = readr::read_csv('data/sample.csv', col_types = readr::cols())

# -> sample id
sample_id = sample_info$sample

# -> a scalar reporting sample purity (0 <= x <= 1)
sample_purity = sample_info$purity

# -> reference genome used
reference = "hg19"

readr returns all tibble-compliant data, using the tidyverse approach. Lets have a look at what we have in the data. To map mutations on top of CNA we need to have genome locations, and to run a deconvolution with MOBSTER we need the VAF of the somatic mutation. Note that these calls are obtained by subtracting the somatic mutations detected in the tumour sample from a putative normal sample, as discussed in the theoretical lecture.

Before moving on, notice that there are driver mutations annotated in these calls; one for instance is an exonic TP53 mutation - identified after Annovar annotations by looking at COSMIC. This driver has been discovered by the authors in the original paper. Another driver event has been retrieved from the original paper, it is a TERT promoter mutation (other potential drivers are annotated in the original paper but the fall off CNA regions, and so are not discussed here).

The input format to include drivers is the one required by CNAqc.

Assessing the quality of these calls

We use the package CNAqc.

The package takes as input all the data we have just loaded, and maps the mutations on top of the segments; it implements also a number of other analyses which we will see right now.

The idea of CNAqc is this. Mutations are somewhat easier to call compared to CNAs, because they are associated to read counts which come out rather directly of a BAM file, while CNAs require complex inference from BAF and log-ratio data. The same holds for sample purity estimate, which is usually obtained together with CNAs.

Thus, in general we can use mutation calls to quality control (QC) CNAs and tumour purity estimates. Basically the two types of data, mutations on one side, and CNAs/purity on the other side, must be consistent.

We begin by creating a CNAqc object; I invite you to read out the outputs of the tool to understand what is happening.

# CNAqc data object
x = CNAqc::init(snvs = snvs,
                cna = cna,
                purity = sample_purity,
                ref = reference, 
                sample = 'Example WGS GBM')
#>  [ CNAqc - CNA Quality Check ]
#>  Using reference genome coordinates for: hg19.

There are some basic plotting functions in the package, you shoud use those to inspect the data.

In general we are interested in the VAF and DP profiles - recall that DP is the coverage per locus. We assemble a nice 2-panels figure by using ggpubr; note that the package also annotates the driver data in the plot, so you can immediately see that this TP53 driver SNVs maps to an LOH region (kind of expected for a suppressor gene).

ggpubr::ggarrange(
  CNAqc::plot_data_histogram(x),
  CNAqc::plot_data_histogram(x, which = 'DP'),
  ncol = 2
  ) %>% 
  print()
#> Warning: Removed 10 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

We can do more complex plots. For instance we can layout a panel with segments in bottom, and all other genome-wide plots on top. Via cowplot we can align plots on the vertical axis, and stretch their relative height to obtain a nice layout.

cowplot::plot_grid(
  CNAqc::plot_gw_counts(x),
  CNAqc::plot_gw_vaf(x, N = 10000),
  CNAqc::plot_gw_depth(x, N = 10000),
  CNAqc::plot_segments(x),
  align = 'v', 
  nrow = 4, 
  rel_heights = c(.15, .15, .15, .8)
  )

So it is easy to see that this tumour is largely diploid

CNAqc::plot_karyotypes(x)

You can play around with the CNAqc functions following examples available at the tool website.

Here we just check that the quality of the calls is good to study this tumour. We use a method based on a peak detection algorithm that is derived from a combinatorial arguments that links tumour ploidy, mutation multiplicity, sample purity, and VAF.

We do not dig into the details of this, you can fin a lot of explanations on the manual and tool website.

Cancer Cell Fractions computation

We can also compute CCFs from these calls, because they are good quality. If everything makes sense, we should obtain the same result we have with diploid mutations.

We compute CCFs values with CNAqc, and plot their analysis. Details on how the computation is carried out are available at the package website. Shortly, it uses an entropy measure based on a mixture model for the expected peaks of mutations multiplicities.

x = CNAqc::compute_CCF(x, method = "ENTROPY")

Subclonal deconvolution of diploid SNVs

We use the package mobster.

Now we know we can trust those diploid SNVs, lets use them.

# Subset the data
diploid_mutations = x %>%
  CNAqc::subset_by_segment_karyotype(karyotypes = '1:1')
#>  [ CNAqc - CNA Quality Check ]
#>  Using reference genome coordinates for: hg19.
#>  Fortified calls for 6728 somatic mutations: 6728 SNVs (100%) and 0 indels.
#> ! CNAs have no CCF, assuming clonal CNAs (CCF = 1).
#>  Fortified CNAs for 198 segments: 198 clonal and 0 subclonal.
#> Warning in map_mutations_to_clonal_segments(snvs, cna_clonal): [CNAqc] a
#> karyotype column is present in CNA calls, and will be overwritten
#>  5984 mutations mapped to clonal CNAs.

# We can visualise the data using ggplot
diploid_mutations$snvs %>%
  ggplot(aes(VAF)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  theme_light()

We use SNVs with VAF above \(5\%\), and below \(65\%\); SNVs above that cut are clearly given by miscalled CNA segments.

We use one possible parametrisation of mobster, which is identified by a "FAST". This tests a few model parameters, and is usually fast to run; It is not necessarily the best analysis but in general is good enough to get a quick grasp of what is in the data.

In this case it works well.

mobster_analysis = mobster_fit(
  diploid_mutations$snvs %>%
    dplyr::filter(VAF > 0.05, VAF < 0.65),  # Remove minimum VAF and obviously wrong mappings
  seed = 1234,
  auto_setup = "FAST",
  description = sample_id
  )
#>  [ MOBSTER fit ]

Function mobster_fit returns a composite object (which we will soon wrap up in a new S3 object). So far you can see the fields returned by the tool in a named list.

The list contains:

  • the best model fits;
  • a set of alternative model fits;
  • a table with all the scored models.
# Named list
names(mobster_analysis)
#> [1] "fits.table"      "runs"            "best"            "model.selection"

# A table reporting the score for each possible model returned by the tool
print(mobster_analysis$fits.table)

The first thing to do now, is to plot the best model fit, and inspect it.

plot(mobster_analysis$best)

Then, we can inspect a number of other features for the model, using other plotting functions of mobster. You should read the model definition to understand exactly what these plot means.

We can see the probability of assignment of a mutation to a cluster, and use it to check if some clusters are more difficult to define than others.

plot_latent_variables(mobster_analysis$best)

Then we can see how big is each cluster (normalised for total mutational burden). In clustering these are called mixing proportions.

plot_mixing_proportions(mobster_analysis$best)

The model minimises a negative log-likelihood function, which we can visualise (as a function of the optimisation step).

plot_NLL(mobster_analysis$best)

In general it is also good to inspect the other models that we have selected as alternative to the best fit.

In this case we see that the only model that makes sense is the best one.

plot_model_selection(mobster_analysis)

The theory underlying mobster allows to retrieve the evolutionary parameters of this tumour, such as:

  • the tumour mutation rate \(\mu\) (in units of cell doublings);
  • the time the subclone originated (same unit as above);
  • the subclone selection coefficient \(s\).
evolutionary_parameters(mobster_analysis)
#> # A tibble: 1  7
#>      mu exponent  time subclonefrequency subclonemutations cluster     s

Subclonal deconvolution with CCF

The CCFs are used to create a valid input for mobster. We rescale the CCF value to match a VAF for a putative heterozygous clonal diploid mutation.

We go faster: we impose filters as above (adjusted for purity), fit the model and visualise it.

# Getter and filter
ccf_input = CNAqc::CCF(x) %>%
  mutate(VAF = CCF/2) %>%
  filter(VAF > 0.05/0.95, VAF < 1)

# Actual run, as above
mobster_analysis_CCF = mobster_fit(
  ccf_input, 
  auto_setup = 'FAST', 
  description = sample_id
  )
#>  [ MOBSTER fit ]

Clone tree inference

We use the package ctree to cpmpute clone trees from these CCF clusters.

This package is accessed directly from mobster. With 1 subclone, there is one possible tree (obviously).

trees = mobster::get_clone_trees(mobster_analysis_CCF$best)
